Intervention Recommendations

Students who may benefit from additional support, identified by comparing scores against grade-level benchmarks.

How concern levels are calculated

Each student's scores are compared against NWEA grade-level benchmarks for the current testing season. Ten equally-weighted signals are evaluated and combined into a composite score (0-100):

SignalWeightFlagged when
Oral Reading
Reading rate performance level10%Below or Approaching
Reading accuracy performance level10%Below or Approaching
Oral Lexile10%Below grade-level threshold (400L Gr2, 500L Gr3, 600L Gr4, 700L Gr5+)
Literal comprehension performance level10%Below or Approaching
Foundational Skills
Phonological awareness percentile10%≤ 25th percentile (more weight if Below, less if Approaching)
Phonics / word recognition percentile10%≤ 25th percentile (more weight if Below, less if Approaching)
PA instructional level (ZPD)10%Below or Approaching grade-level expectation
Phonics instructional level (ZPD)10%Below or Approaching grade-level expectation
Listening comprehension performance level10%Below or Approaching
Picture vocabulary10%Below grade-level expectation

When a signal is unavailable (e.g., no oral reading data for K), its weight is redistributed across the remaining signals.

Oral reading and foundational skills benchmarks are weighted evenly because some schools administer both an oral reading and a foundational skills assessment during the same testing window, giving each student two benchmark results per term.

Sentence Reading Fluency is not included as a signal because it serves as the adaptive gateway that determines whether a student advances from the foundational skills portion of the test to the oral reading portion. It is a routing mechanism, not an independent measure of skill.

Concern tiers: Critical (≥60) High (≥40) Moderate (≥25) Watch (≥10)
Focus areas: Below Approaching
Student ID ↕ Student ↕ Grade ↕ Homeroom ↕ Concern Level ↕ WCPM ↕ Accuracy ↕ Lexile ↕ Focus Areas ↕ Recommendation ↕

🎯 MAP Growth Intervention Recommendations

?

Students who may need additional support based on MAP Growth performance indicators.

How Concern Level is Calculated (2 Signals, scored per course):

Each course is scored independently — a student can be Critical in Reading but Watch in Math.

1. SDs Below National Norm
80% weight (max 80 pts)		How far below the US national average is the student's End RIT? Scored by standard deviations: 1 SD ≈ 30 pts, 2 SD ≈ 60 pts, 2.7+ SD = 80 pts. A student 2+ SDs below is Critical even with on-track growth. Students at or above the norm receive 0 points.
2. Growth Shortfall
20% weight (max 20 pts)		Growth efficiency = Observed Growth ÷ Projected Growth. Students who met or exceeded their projection receive 0 points. Below 100%, points scale proportionally. Negative growth reaches the max 20 pts. Growth alone cannot push a student above Watch/Moderate.
Concern Tiers: Critical (≥60%), High (≥40%), Moderate (≥25%), Watch (≥10%)
Concern tiers: Critical (≥60) High (≥40) Moderate (≥25) Watch (≥10)
0 students identified
Student ID ↕ Student ↕ Grade ↕ Homeroom ↕ Course ↕ Concern ↕ End RIT ↕ Natl Norm ↕ SDs Below ↕ Obs Growth ↕ Proj Growth ↕ Met Proj ↕ Recommendation ↕

Import Data

MAP Growth requires the Achievement Status and Growth (ASG) report from NWEA MAP.

1. Go to NWEA MAP Reports → Achievement Status and Growth
2. Select your school, term, and classes
3. Choose Projection or Summary view
4. Click Create Spreadsheet to download the CSV
5. Import a separate CSV for each term

Note: This CSV is just an example of the expected format. You do not need to use this template — the CSV export from MAP can be directly imported.

National norms are used for percentile calculations, chart annotations, and risk assessments across the app.

MAP Reading Fluency Excel Import

The Excel file should contain:
• One sheet per term — name each sheet with the term (e.g., "Fall 25-26", "Winter 25-26", "Spring 25-26")
• ClassList sheet (optional) — contains homeroom assignments (columns: StudentID, HomeroomTeacher, ClassName).
• Note: If MAP Growth data is uploaded, the app will use the ClassName from MAP Growth automatically, so a ClassList sheet is not required. If a ClassList sheet is included, it will take priority over the MAP Growth ClassName.

    Privacy Policy

    This application processes all data entirely within your web browser. No student data, assessment scores, or personally identifiable information is transmitted to any external server, cloud service, or third party at any time.

    Data Handling

    • All uploaded files (MAP Growth CSV, MAP Reading Fluency Excel) are parsed and processed locally using client-side JavaScript.
    • Data is stored temporarily in your browser's IndexedDB for session persistence. This data remains on your device and is never sent externally.
    • Generated reports, charts, and exports (PDF, XLSX, HTML, ZIP) are created locally in your browser and saved directly to your device.

    Data Portability & Sharing

    • The dashboard file itself contains no student data. Sharing or distributing the HTML file does not transfer any uploaded data — it will open as a blank dashboard.
    • To share a working dashboard with data, the recipient must separately receive and import the original data files (CSV/Excel).

    No Data Collection

    • This application does not collect, store, transmit, or log any user data or student information.
    • No cookies, analytics, or tracking of any kind are used.
    • No user accounts or authentication are required.

    Data Retention

    • Browser-stored data persists only until manually cleared by the user or until browser storage is cleared.
    • Closing the browser or clearing site data removes all stored information.

    User Responsibility

    Users are solely responsible for handling exported files and student data in compliance with their institution's data privacy policies and applicable regulations (e.g., FERPA, GDPR). The developer assumes no liability for how exported data is stored, shared, or managed after leaving this application.

    Getting Started

    Importing Data

    Click the Import button in the header to upload your assessment data.

    • MAP Growth — Upload a CSV file exported from NWEA MAP. Go to MAP Reports, select the Comprehensive Data File (or Academic Status & Growth report), and download as CSV.
    • MAP Reading Fluency — Upload an Excel (.xlsx) file with one sheet per term (e.g., Fall 25-26, Winter 25-26). An optional ClassList sheet can map students to homerooms.
    • You can download template files from the import dialog to see the expected format.

    Navigating the Dashboard

    • Use the top tabs to switch between MAP Growth, MAP Reading Fluency, and Student Reports.
    • Each test type has its own sub-tabs (School Dashboard, Grade Level Report, Homeroom Report, Interventions, etc.).
    • Use the term buttons in the header to filter data by assessment period (Fall, Winter, Spring).
    • Each test type remembers its selected term independently.

    Norms Year

    The NWEA Norms Year selector (found in the MAP Growth settings area) lets you choose between 2015, 2020, or 2025 normative data. This affects all national norm reference lines, percentile calculations, and risk assessments. The default is 2025.

    Exporting & Sharing

    • Reports can be exported as PDF, HTML, or XLSX from their respective panels.
    • Student reports can be exported individually or in bulk as a ZIP file.

    Data Security

    All data stays in your browser — nothing is sent to any server. The dashboard HTML file contains no student data, so sharing the file with a colleague will not expose any information. To share a working dashboard, send the HTML file along with the CSV/Excel data files separately. See the Privacy Policy for full details.
